                <head>12. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On April 23, 1970, Presidentʼs Assistant for National Security Affairs <persName
                        corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry Kissinger</persName> sent a memorandum to the
                    Secretaries of State, Defense, and Commerce on the issue of export controls.
                    Copies were sent to the Director of Central Intelligence, the Chairman of the
                    Atomic Energy Commission, and the Administrator of the National Aeronautics and
                    Space Administration. The memorandum reads, in part, as follows:</p>
                <p>“The President has made the following decisions on this subject [export controls]
                    on the basis of several memoranda recently submitted by the Secretary of
                    Commerce: <list>
                        <item>“1. The list of items and data subject to control for export to the
                                <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss> and the Communist countries of
                            Eastern Europe should henceforth be limited to: <list>
                                <item>“a. <gloss target="#t_COCOM1">COCOM</gloss> items</item>
                                <item>“b. Those non-<gloss target="#t_COCOM1">COCOM</gloss>
                                    commodities and technical data, which, in the judgment of the
                                    U.S., could contribute significantly to the development,
                                    production, or use of military hardware, or to the
                                    military-supporting industrial capability of the <gloss
                                        target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss> and the countries of Eastern
                                    Europe, to the detriment of our national security, regardless of
                                    foreign availability….</item>
                            </list>
                        </item>
                        <pb facs="0065" n="21" xml:id="pg_21"/>
                        <item>“3. Decisions on specific cases should take account of over-all <gloss
                                target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> policy toward the specific country for
                            which the export is destined. At present, this would mean, for example,
                            more liberal treatment for Romania than for other Eastern European
                            states.”</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>For the full text of the memorandum, see <ref target="frus1969-76v04#d318">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1969–1976, volume IV, Foreign
                        Assistance, International Development, Trade Policies, 1969–1972, Document
                        318</ref>.</p>
